{"format": "tiptap/v1", "doc": {"type": "doc", "content": [{"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "The Fundamental Difference"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "An RNN processes a sequence one token at a time — step 2 cannot start until step 1 finishes, because step 2 needs the hidden state produced by step 1. A transformer processes all positions "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "simultaneously in a single matrix multiply"}, {"type": "text", "text": ". This single difference is what makes transformers trainable at scale: GPUs are designed to execute thousands of operations in parallel, and the transformer's attention mechanism maps directly onto batched matrix multiplication."}]}, {"type": "image", "attrs": {"src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,", "alt": "RNN sequential processing vs transformer parallel attention, with complexity comparison table including state space models"}}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Why RNNs Are Sequential"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "An RNN cell computes a new hidden state from the current input and the previous hidden state:"}]}, {"type": "blockMath", "attrs": {"latex": "h_t = f(W_h h_{t-1} + W_x x_t + b)"}}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "The dependency on "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "code"}], "text": "h_{t-1}"}, {"type": "text", "text": " creates a hard sequential chain. To compute "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "code"}], "text": "h_T"}, {"type": "text", "text": ", you must compute "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "code"}], "text": "h_{T-1}"}, {"type": "text", "text": ", which requires "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "code"}], "text": "h_{T-2}"}, {"type": "text", "text": ", and so on. No matter how many GPUs you have, you cannot parallelise this chain. Training on a sequence of length T requires T sequential steps."}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Backpropagation through time (BPTT) faces the same problem in reverse: gradients flow from "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "code"}], "text": "h_T"}, {"type": "text", "text": " back to "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "code"}], "text": "h_1"}, {"type": "text", "text": " sequentially. For long sequences this not only makes training slow but also leads to vanishing or exploding gradients, because the same weight matrix "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "code"}], "text": "W_h"}, {"type": "text", "text": " is multiplied T times during backprop."}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn as nn\nimport time\n\nd_model, seq_len = 512, 512\nbatch = 8\n\n# RNN: sequential over time\nrnn = nn.GRU(d_model, d_model, batch_first=True).cuda()\nx   = torch.randn(batch, seq_len, d_model, device='cuda')\n\ntorch.cuda.synchronize()\nt0 = time.time()\nfor _ in range(100):\n    out, _ = rnn(x)\ntorch.cuda.synchronize()\nprint(f'RNN:         {(time.time()-t0)*10:.1f} ms/iter')\n\n# Transformer: parallel over sequence\nattn = nn.MultiheadAttention(d_model, num_heads=8, batch_first=True).cuda()\nmask = torch.tril(torch.ones(seq_len, seq_len, device='cuda')).bool()\n\ntorch.cuda.synchronize()\nt0 = time.time()\nfor _ in range(100):\n    out, _ = attn(x, x, x, attn_mask=~mask)\ntorch.cuda.synchronize()\nprint(f'Transformer: {(time.time()-t0)*10:.1f} ms/iter')\n# Transformer is typically 5-20x faster at seq_len=512 on a modern GPU"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Why Transformers Are Parallel"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "In the transformer, the query–key dot products for all pairs of positions can be computed in a single batched matrix multiplication:"}]}, {"type": "blockMath", "attrs": {"latex": "\\text{Scores} = QK^\\top \\in \\mathbb{R}^{T \\times T}"}}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "There is no recurrence — position 100's output does not depend on position 99's output having been computed first. Every position's output depends only on the input embeddings (which are all available before any computation starts) and the learned weight matrices. This means all T positions can be processed in parallel depth O(1)."}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "During training with teacher forcing, all T target token predictions are computed in a single forward pass. The causal mask simply zeroes out future positions in the attention matrix — it does not introduce sequential computation. The whole batch of T predictions and T loss values is computed together."}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "import torch\n\nT, d_model, d_k = 6, 512, 64\n\n# All Q, K, V computed from input X in parallel\nX = torch.randn(T, d_model)   # all T tokens available at once\nWq = torch.randn(d_model, d_k)\nWk = torch.randn(d_model, d_k)\nWv = torch.randn(d_model, d_k)\n\nQ = X @ Wq   # (T, d_k) — all T queries at once\nK = X @ Wk   # (T, d_k) — all T keys at once\nV = X @ Wv   # (T, d_k) — all T values at once\n\n# All T×T scores in one matmul — no loop over positions\nscores = Q @ K.T / d_k**0.5   # (T, T)\n\n# Causal mask — computed once, not sequentially\ncausal_mask = torch.tril(torch.ones(T, T, dtype=torch.bool))\nscores = scores.masked_fill(~causal_mask, float('-inf'))\nattn = torch.softmax(scores, dim=-1)\nout  = attn @ V   # (T, d_k) — all T outputs at once\nprint(out.shape)  # (6, 64) — all 6 positions computed together"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "The Inference Trade-off"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Parallelism is a training advantage only. At inference time, transformers become sequential again — they must generate one token at a time, and each new token requires re-running attention over the entire prefix. The "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "KV cache"}, {"type": "text", "text": " mitigates this by storing keys and values from previous tokens so they don't need to be recomputed — but the cache grows linearly with context length, consuming memory."}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "RNNs have the opposite profile: at inference they are O(1) per step with a fixed-size hidden state regardless of how much context has been processed. This is why RNN-like architectures (Mamba, RWKV, GLA) are an active area of research — they combine the parallel training of linear recurrences with the constant-cost inference of fixed hidden states."}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Parallelism at Scale: Data, Model, and Pipeline"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "The transformer's parallelism over sequence positions is one of three axes used to scale LLM training across thousands of GPUs:"}]}, {"type": "bulletList", "content": [{"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Data parallelism"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": different GPUs process different batches simultaneously and average gradients. Scales with number of GPUs linearly."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Tensor (model) parallelism"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": split the weight matrices of individual attention heads or FFN layers across GPUs. Each GPU holds a shard of every layer."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Pipeline parallelism"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": different GPUs hold different layers. Microbatches flow through the pipeline, keeping all stages active."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Sequence parallelism"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": split the sequence dimension across GPUs. Different GPUs attend to different token ranges, communicating KV states via ring all-reduce. Enables training on contexts too long to fit on one GPU."}]}]}]}, {"type": "blockquote", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Why parallelism is the decisive advantage: "}, {"type": "text", "text": "GPT-3's 175B parameters were trained on roughly 300 billion tokens in a matter of weeks using thousands of A100s. The same training run with an LSTM would have taken orders of magnitude longer — not because LSTMs are less capable per operation, but because they cannot use the GPU's parallel processing units. The transformer didn't just make attention better; it made the whole of deep learning's hardware advantage available to sequence modelling."}]}]}]}}